00:22:44.408 --> 00:22:46.660
Now. can we please start over?

257
00:22:52.416 --> 00:22:54.751
Okay. Where are the cars?

258
00:22:55.711 --> 00:22:56.712
Stop.

259
00:22:58.714 --> 00:22:59.798
Stop.

260
00:23:05.053 --> 00:23:07.222
Elvis had a shit ton of
cars and we wanna see 'em.

261
00:23:14.771 --> 00:23:16.624
I... I don't... I don't know. I
don't know where they are.

262
00:23:16.648 --> 00:23:19.377
We had some here.

263
00:23:19.401 --> 00:23:21.588
The others were across
the street in the exhibit hall.

264
00:23:21.612 --> 00:23:23.412
but I haven't been
there in years. I don't...

265
00:23:28.410 --> 00:23:29.703
You too.

266
00:23:46.136 --> 00:23:47.387
They call me link.

267
00:23:49.556 --> 00:23:50.849
We'll do intros later.

268
00:23:54.728 --> 00:23:56.146
Come here. sit.

269
00:24:13.789 --> 00:24:16.917
It's. a peace offering. You look cold.

270
00:24:21.588 --> 00:24:23.608
How'd you get to Graceland?

271
00:24:23.632 --> 00:24:25.801
I was a tour guide here
when it all happened.

272
00:24:26.802 --> 00:24:28.804
You've been here alone the entire time?

273
00:24:41.566 --> 00:24:43.461
Looks like you never built a fire.

274
00:24:43.485 --> 00:24:45.237
I didn't want anyone to see the smoke.

275
00:24:46.238 --> 00:24:48.573
I didn't want anyone to know I was here.

276
00:24:49.950 --> 00:24:50.951
Smart.

277
00:24:53.996 --> 00:24:55.598
Well...

278
00:24:55.622 --> 00:24:58.250
I absolutely love what
you've done with the place.

279
00:25:12.222 --> 00:25:15.743
It must have been hard
being here... on your own.

280
00:25:15.767 --> 00:25:17.311
I've been alone before.

281
00:25:19.271 --> 00:25:20.939
Must have been hard all the same.

282
00:26:01.021 --> 00:26:02.938
I really must insist
we get this thing tune...

283
00:26:04.983 --> 00:26:08.320
fuck. Jesus Christ.

284
00:26:20.415 --> 00:26:22.727
Fuck!

285
00:26:22.751 --> 00:26:25.253
I wasn't gonna hurt you. okay?

286
00:26:31.301 --> 00:26:33.303
Enough for all of us.

287
00:26:49.361 --> 00:26:51.756
Yeah. geiger. next time.
pick a smaller boar to kill.

288
00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:54.824
Hey. man. you guys said get
enough for everybody. so I don't know.

289
00:27:01.498 --> 00:27:02.850
I'm gonna give it to you
straight. but I want you

290
00:27:02.874 --> 00:27:04.102
to keep an open mind about it.

291
00:27:04.126 --> 00:27:06.479
This is the deal. alright?
We Jack a sailboat.

292
00:27:06.503 --> 00:27:08.689
Already a bad start. Terrible start.

293
00:27:08.713 --> 00:27:10.172
No. just hear me out!

294
00:27:14.136 --> 00:27:16.781
- Chef's making bacon.
- Wild boar.

295
00:27:16.805 --> 00:27:19.391
Still qualifies. Sit.

296
00:27:27.899 --> 00:27:29.377
Little appetizer.

297
00:27:29.401 --> 00:27:31.069
You were in that room for three days.

298
00:27:34.948 --> 00:27:36.717
Eat. Drink.

299
00:27:36.741 --> 00:27:39.327
Alright? You can relax.
We're not the bad guys.

300
00:27:43.123 --> 00:27:45.351
Though I will admit to
not being my best self

301
00:27:45.375 --> 00:27:48.479
since the grade-two concussion
you gave the best piano player

302
00:27:48.503 --> 00:27:49.753
this place has seen in years.

303
00:27:58.013 --> 00:28:00.366
So. the good news. after three years.

304
00:28:00.390 --> 00:28:02.851
things are better out
there than you think.

305
00:28:03.977 --> 00:28:07.230
I asked you your name
before. but you spat on me.

306
00:28:08.231 --> 00:28:11.210
- Twice.
- Yes. twice. Thank you. geiger.

307
00:28:11.234 --> 00:28:13.588
This is geiger. He's great at counting.

308
00:28:13.612 --> 00:28:14.905
You got a name?

309
00:28:16.364 --> 00:28:17.633
Annie.

310
00:28:17.657 --> 00:28:20.011
- Annie. my name is...
- link.

311
00:28:20.035 --> 00:28:21.244
Yeah. you said.

312
00:28:22.454 --> 00:28:24.640
Left a Mark.

313
00:28:24.664 --> 00:28:28.519
A little about me. since I don't
exactly have Instagram anymore.

314
00:28:28.543 --> 00:28:31.314
when the shit hit the fan.
I was living in louisville.

315
00:28:31.338 --> 00:28:34.775
Dropped out of college. got a job at rei.

316
00:28:34.799 --> 00:28:38.696
and I heard the words "super
volcano" and "ash cloud" on the news.

317
00:28:38.720 --> 00:28:42.200
and I grabbed as much north
face swag as I possibly could.

318
00:28:42.224 --> 00:28:44.368
Everyone else was making
a run. you know. for guns

319
00:28:44.392 --> 00:28:47.163
and for toilet paper. while I was shoving

320
00:28:47.187 --> 00:28:50.458
antarctic-rated sleeping
bags in my Ford focus.

321
00:28:50.482 --> 00:28:52.210
Saved my life.

322
00:28:52.234 --> 00:28:53.860
No. I saved your life.

323
00:28:53.985 --> 00:28:56.339
It's my story. geiger.
Can I tell it for once?

324
00:28:56.363 --> 00:28:59.425
I'm just asking for a little
fidelity to the truth. partner.

325
00:28:59.449 --> 00:29:01.552
I mean. when I found you.

326
00:29:01.576 --> 00:29:03.763
you were in a sleeping
bag crying like a toddler.

327
00:29:03.787 --> 00:29:05.139
So. let's not make it out

328
00:29:05.163 --> 00:29:06.933
like you were Richard
hatch or something.

329
00:29:06.957 --> 00:29:08.351
- Richard hatch is...
- yeah. I know.

330
00:29:08.375 --> 00:29:10.811
He won the first season of <i>survivor.</i>

331
00:29:10.835 --> 00:29:12.188
Nice.

332
00:29:12.212 --> 00:29:15.066
Anyway. geiger here fed me.

333
00:29:15.090 --> 00:29:17.360
Not because he loved me instantly.

334
00:29:17.384 --> 00:29:19.987
but because he needed
another set of hands.

335
00:29:20.011 --> 00:29:21.280
Go ahead.

336
00:29:21.304 --> 00:29:23.032
We tell this story a lot. This is his part.

337
00:29:23.056 --> 00:29:25.368
I was recruiting a crew to go around

338
00:29:25.392 --> 00:29:29.247
and safely shut down all
the nuclear power plants.

339
00:29:29.271 --> 00:29:32.333
There's 94 in the country.
All of them are just meltdowns

340
00:29:32.357 --> 00:29:34.377
waiting to happen if they're abandoned.

341
00:29:34.401 --> 00:29:36.045
- And that's job one.
- Yeah.

342
00:29:36.069 --> 00:29:37.797
We've been everywhere
this side of Mississippi

343
00:29:37.821 --> 00:29:39.364
that isn't underwater.

344
00:29:40.991 --> 00:29:42.826
So. how much do you
know about what happened?

345
00:29:45.287 --> 00:29:48.849
Best we can... actually.
well. this is urkel's section.

346
00:29:48.873 --> 00:29:50.583
We call him... we call
him urkel because...

347
00:29:50.607 --> 00:29:51.686
if she knew Richard hatch.

348
00:29:51.710 --> 00:29:53.688
I'm guessing she can crack urkel.

349
00:29:53.712 --> 00:29:56.482
Thanks. Best we can tell.

350
00:29:56.506 --> 00:29:58.651
volcanic eruption didn't
just create a Tsunami

351
00:29:58.675 --> 00:30:01.028
that flooded the coastal areas.

352
00:30:01.052 --> 00:30:03.406
It was so intense. the ash cloud

353
00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:06.200
went into the stratosphere
and circled the earth.

354
00:30:06.224 --> 00:30:09.728
cooling the planet by
20 degrees or more.

355
00:30:10.645 --> 00:30:12.540
I have a theory that
one of the world powers

356
00:30:12.564 --> 00:30:16.043
had a secret emp device
that knocked out all electronics.

357
00:30:16.067 --> 00:30:18.087
- I mean. anything with a battery...
- Alright. alright. alright.

358
00:30:18.111 --> 00:30:20.256
Don't let him go down the emp road.

359
00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:22.216
otherwise. you'll be
praying for another Tsunami.

360
00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:23.325
- Trust me.
- We'll talk.

361
00:30:24.492 --> 00:30:26.411
Upshot is...

362
00:30:29.456 --> 00:30:31.851
It was bad. It was really fucking bad.

363
00:30:31.875 --> 00:30:35.771
We believe that we lost
two-thirds of the U.S. population.

364
00:30:35.795 --> 00:30:39.025
the first 40% from the
Tsunami that hit the coast.

365
00:30:39.049 --> 00:30:43.970
the next 27% from. I don't
know. societal collapse. starvation.

366
00:30:45.388 --> 00:30:48.951
Any survivors that we meet
now are people in groups

367
00:30:48.975 --> 00:30:50.786
who have figured out
how to work together.

368
00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:54.123
and most importantly. how to
grow food in these conditions.

369
00:30:54.147 --> 00:30:56.834
And speaking of!

370
00:30:56.858 --> 00:31:00.296
Hey. big papi here was impressed
with your plant in the window.

371
00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:02.238
Yeah. Needs more light. though.

372
00:31:03.615 --> 00:31:08.012
So. you guys. where can I
get some motherfucking bacon?

373
00:31:08.036 --> 00:31:09.722
Boom.

374
00:31:09.746 --> 00:31:12.099
Ooh. yeah. Man. I love this.

375
00:31:12.123 --> 00:31:13.500
Hey.

376
00:31:14.417 --> 00:31:17.104
You don't have to hide in your room.

377
00:31:17.128 --> 00:31:18.314
Okay?

378
00:31:18.338 --> 00:31:20.900
Hopefully. you don't mind
having a few new roommates

379
00:31:20.924 --> 00:31:22.151
for the next few days.

380
00:31:22.175 --> 00:31:24.427
We'll be out of your hair soon.

381
00:31:25.345 --> 00:31:27.054
Spring break can't last forever.

382
00:31:47.742 --> 00:31:49.553
Holy shit!

383
00:31:49.577 --> 00:31:51.347
The king does not disappoint. gentlemen.

384
00:31:51.371 --> 00:31:53.265
Alright. let's see what we got.

385
00:31:53.289 --> 00:31:54.832
You feeling that. that's yours.

386
00:31:59.629 --> 00:32:01.881
Don't worry. ma'am.
We're not gonna take 'em.

387
00:32:02.715 --> 00:32:05.694
Just some parts. Cars are
pretty much worthless now.

388
00:32:05.718 --> 00:32:07.679
Fucker.

389
00:32:08.638 --> 00:32:10.181
- You alright?
- Yeah. yeah. yeah.

390
00:32:11.182 --> 00:32:13.059
- Good?
- Yeah. yeah. It's fine.

391
00:32:15.562 --> 00:32:18.124
The only access in
here is from the south.

392
00:32:18.148 --> 00:32:21.168
I think we should stage
here. set up a perimeter.

393
00:32:21.192 --> 00:32:23.712
This place is gonna be seriously fortified.

394
00:32:23.736 --> 00:32:25.840
Do we have the firepower? Yes.

395
00:32:25.864 --> 00:32:29.117
Even if we get in. how
are we gonna find her?

396
00:32:30.743 --> 00:32:32.870
Hey. we're just planning
our next road trip.

397
00:32:35.081 --> 00:32:36.665
Okay.

398
00:32:43.882 --> 00:32:46.902
Yeah. we. we all take
those. Preventative.

399
00:32:46.926 --> 00:32:49.989
- Potassium iodide?
- Yeah.

400
00:32:50.013 --> 00:32:52.098
You know. this is only
good for hyperthyroidism.

401
00:32:53.183 --> 00:32:54.976
It doesn't help with radiation exposure.

402
00:32:55.977 --> 00:32:57.145
Thanks. we know.

403
00:33:00.982 --> 00:33:03.210
How long your wrist been like that?

404
00:33:03.234 --> 00:33:04.628
Couple months.

405
00:33:04.652 --> 00:33:07.047
You know. saving the world.
it gets rough sometimes.

406
00:33:07.071 --> 00:33:09.282
It hurts. but I can manage.

407
00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:12.368
I think it's just a scaphoid fracture.

408
00:33:13.786 --> 00:33:15.514
- What?
- It's a small bone near the base

409
00:33:15.538 --> 00:33:18.642
of your thumb. I can reset it.

410
00:33:18.666 --> 00:33:20.853
- Come here.
- Yeah? If...

411
00:33:20.877 --> 00:33:26.650
My hands are cold. but just... Yeah. okay.

412
00:33:26.674 --> 00:33:28.819
Ye... oof. Yeah. you
have to find the bone.

413
00:33:28.843 --> 00:33:32.615
and then kind of just. like.
knock it back into place.

414
00:33:32.639 --> 00:33:33.908
Sorry. you okay?

415
00:33:33.932 --> 00:33:35.159
Yeah.

416
00:33:35.183 --> 00:33:37.203
- Oof.
- I'll... I'll make you a splint.

417
00:33:37.227 --> 00:33:39.079
but you should probably try not
to use it for the next few weeks.

418
00:33:39.103 --> 00:33:40.104
Alright.

419
00:33:41.105 --> 00:33:42.148
Thanks.

420
00:34:07.549 --> 00:34:09.318
You remember this place?

421
00:34:09.342 --> 00:34:11.582
I can't wait to hear about all
your adventures. Come on.

422
00:34:13.012 --> 00:34:14.847
It looks like you've been through a lot.

423
00:34:15.848 --> 00:34:18.141
I missed you so much.

424
00:34:28.236 --> 00:34:30.881
Sorry. I didn't know anyone was up here.

425
00:34:30.905 --> 00:34:32.716
No. I hope this is okay.

426
00:34:32.740 --> 00:34:34.617
I'll... I'll move it back when I'm done.

427
00:34:36.160 --> 00:34:37.161
Yeah.

428
00:34:51.050 --> 00:34:52.736
I wondered if we'd
ever see the stars again

429
00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:54.429
after that ash cloud was up there.

430
00:34:56.055 --> 00:34:59.726
Do you ever see any satellites?
They look like shooting stars.

431
00:35:01.477 --> 00:35:03.687
They're all starting to
fall out of the sky now.

432
00:35:11.738 --> 00:35:12.947
I have.

433
00:35:15.658 --> 00:35:18.453
Yeah. I wondered why there
were so many shooting stars.

434
00:35:24.876 --> 00:35:26.294
Satellites.

435
00:35:28.504 --> 00:35:29.797
Of course.

436
00:35:32.383 --> 00:35:34.761
Man. I used to fucking love telescopes.

437
00:35:36.137 --> 00:35:37.263
Outer space.

438
00:35:43.019 --> 00:35:45.355
Went to Florida when I was a kid.

439
00:35:46.356 --> 00:35:49.418
And my sister would
not stop going on and on

440
00:35:49.442 --> 00:35:51.795
about Disney world.

441
00:35:51.819 --> 00:35:54.030
but I was way more
hyped on cape canaveral.

442
00:35:55.198 --> 00:35:57.051
You ever been?

443
00:35:57.075 --> 00:35:58.868
No? Aw. man. it was the shit.

444
00:35:59.911 --> 00:36:02.640
I mean. it's not there anymore since...

445
00:36:02.664 --> 00:36:04.916
over a decade ago.

446
00:36:06.417 --> 00:36:08.312
How old are you?

447
00:36:08.336 --> 00:36:11.297
It's hard to keep track.
but I think I turned...

448
00:36:12.548 --> 00:36:13.883
25 this year?

449
00:36:14.801 --> 00:36:16.219
You're 25?

450
00:36:17.220 --> 00:36:20.199
- Wow.
- I mean. it's been a rough few years.

451
00:36:20.223 --> 00:36:22.534
It's not easy to maintain
a skincare routine.

452
00:36:22.558 --> 00:36:24.078
No. I think it's just the beard.

453
00:36:24.102 --> 00:36:26.497
Well. the beard makes
me look like a leader.

454
00:36:26.521 --> 00:36:28.321
The beard makes you
look like Charles man son.

455
00:36:30.775 --> 00:36:31.776
Okay.

456
00:36:45.081 --> 00:36:47.917
That was me my
freshman year of college.

457
00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:51.355
Wow. You're a baby.

458
00:36:51.379 --> 00:36:54.215
- Yep.
- Cute.

459
00:36:57.176 --> 00:37:00.221
You can keep it if you want.

460
00:37:02.432 --> 00:37:03.599
Thank you.

461
00:37:07.145 --> 00:37:08.730
Why do they call you link?

462
00:37:09.897 --> 00:37:12.024
It's the main guy from <i>Zelda.</i>

463
00:37:14.444 --> 00:37:17.423
Yeah. We seem like
a bunch of bad-asses.

464
00:37:17.447 --> 00:37:21.325
but we're actually just a bunch of
nerds who outlasted the popular kids.

465
00:37:22.702 --> 00:37:24.787
I kinda got that.

466
00:37:27.248 --> 00:37:29.500
Well. we are in fact leaving tomorrow.

467
00:37:30.793 --> 00:37:33.689
We're part of this bigger group of people

468
00:37:33.713 --> 00:37:38.051
going out west to try
and restart the world.

469
00:37:40.219 --> 00:37:41.971
I gotta be in St. Louis by next week.

470
00:37:43.389 --> 00:37:45.683
Why are you going up to St.
Louis if you're heading west?

471
00:37:46.684 --> 00:37:49.562
Because you don't want to be
crossing the river into Arkansas.

472
00:37:51.105 --> 00:37:52.857
It's not so bad anymore. but...

473
00:37:54.525 --> 00:37:56.277
There's still some bad pockets.

474
00:37:57.528 --> 00:37:59.113
Like. you see right over there?

475
00:38:00.490 --> 00:38:02.825
See just across the river?

476
00:38:03.826 --> 00:38:05.078
That's a bad pocket.

477
00:38:09.373 --> 00:38:12.853
So. since it's our last night.

478
00:38:12.877 --> 00:38:15.129
what are your dinner plans?

479
00:38:16.547 --> 00:38:20.402
Because there's this new
place just opened up downstairs.

480
00:38:20.426 --> 00:38:22.613
and they just got a new chef last week

481
00:38:22.637 --> 00:38:25.098
who's just completely
revamped the menu.

482
00:38:39.153 --> 00:38:41.381
Okay? At least I look sharp.

483
00:38:41.405 --> 00:38:43.258
I look sharp. you're in a sweatshirt.

484
00:38:43.282 --> 00:38:44.635
It says. "do good." though.

485
00:38:44.659 --> 00:38:46.804
All the costumes in this
house. that's what you grab.

486
00:38:46.828 --> 00:38:48.764
- You guys. you're both pretty.
- Whoa!

487
00:38:48.788 --> 00:38:51.767
- Wow.
- Stop.

488
00:38:51.791 --> 00:38:54.269
You look nice. Annie.

489
00:38:54.293 --> 00:38:56.230
Thank you.

490
00:38:56.254 --> 00:38:58.089
It smells great down here.

491
00:39:00.133 --> 00:39:02.236
Link will be here in a minute.

492
00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:03.927
She takes a while to get dressed.

493
00:39:07.265 --> 00:39:09.618
- One for the lady.
- There she is!

494
00:39:09.642 --> 00:39:11.434
Cinderella!

495
00:39:14.021 --> 00:39:18.001
Yeah? Alright. Alright. assholes.

496
00:39:18.025 --> 00:39:19.336
Alright. shut the fuck up.

497
00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:21.672
Isn't she pretty?

498
00:39:21.696 --> 00:39:23.215
- She's so lovely.
- My god.

499
00:39:23.239 --> 00:39:25.992
Wow.

500
00:39:28.035 --> 00:39:29.704
Wow. You...

501
00:39:30.913 --> 00:39:33.892
- You look really pretty.
- Thank you.

502
00:39:33.916 --> 00:39:36.186
So. what do you think?

503
00:39:36.210 --> 00:39:37.962
I...

504
00:39:38.963 --> 00:39:41.256
I was wrong. I... I miss the beard.

505
00:39:42.633 --> 00:39:44.027
Ouch.

506
00:39:44.051 --> 00:39:45.802
One for the prettiest boy at the table.

507
00:39:47.471 --> 00:39:49.199
Thank you. Alright. alright.

508
00:39:49.223 --> 00:39:51.535
A big thank you to our lovely host.

509
00:39:51.559 --> 00:39:55.396
Cheers.

510
00:39:59.150 --> 00:40:01.795
'Kay. Annie. One thing you
miss. one thing you don't.

511
